The functionality to retrieve MARC directly from Alma may be removed, and replaced with retrieving the indexed version from Orangelight. However, it may still be possible to retrieve metadata for suppressed records from Orangelight. Pulfalight has a similiar use case, and some options are being considered: falling back on retrieving from ASpace, or indexing a minimal version of the record (e.g., just the title). We might consider similar approaches in Orangelight.

princeton_ansible.title: adds keepalive values to postgresql config
Set tcp_keepalives params in postgres configuration

comments.body: Do any of our projects create long-running connections to postgresql that go dormant for more than 5 minutes but that we do not want to drop?

Notes from the DACS meeting today:
- We have some processes that need long-running connections, but we also need to make sure we don't use all available connections up. Searching for a middle TCP keepalive setting for postgres that will work for all applications.
- Current bibdata error in [honeybadger](https://app.honeybadger.io/projects/54497/faults/87507590). This error happens about every 6 hours, regularly, this is probably caused by the “create” step, seems to be part of the incremental index. This error is caused by hanging on too long and then running out of available connections.
- Postgres solution to the problem of radically different demands from different applications is to set up a separate system to allocate TCP connections, but we'd rather not do that unless we have to.
- Similar errors can be caused by memory shortages, but the bibdata worker boxes only use 5% of their available memory, and the pgsql boxes use at most about 60% of theirs, so memory does not seem to be the issue here.
- The problem may be coming from the SQS poller, which connects every 5 seconds - see [the code here](https://github.com/pulibrary/bibdata/blob/6630d8cadbfb8acd8a34aff7664e8821acb313d6/app/services/aws_sqs_poller.rb#L23).
- A next step would be to try recreating this error on staging by running those commands in the rails console.
Here's a tool @hackartisan found that might be helpful in testing our changes: https://github.com/supabase/pg_netstat
